Claude Sonnet 4.5 vs Opus 4.5 for Claude Code

Claude Sonnet 4.5 and Claude Opus 4.5 serve different roles in Claude Code workflows. Sonnet 4.5 is excellent for fast daily coding work, while Opus 4.5 is state-of-the-art for software engineering (leading SWE-bench Verified), complex reasoning, and agentic workflows. Understanding their strengths helps you optimize both performance and costs.

Experience advanced architecture (ad)

How to Choose Between Them​

Set Claude Sonnet 4.5 as your default for daily coding work (excellent speed and cost-efficiency), then switch to Opus 4.5 for state-of-the-art software engineering:

# Set Sonnet 4.5 as default (excellent for daily coding)
export ANTHROPIC_MODEL="claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929"

# Switch to Opus 4.5 for state-of-the-art software engineering
claude --model claude-opus-4-5-20251101 "Analyze system architecture trade-offs"

Use Sonnet 4.5 for routine coding tasks. It's fast, cost-effective, and handles most development work excellently. Use Opus 4.5 when you need state-of-the-art software engineering capabilities.

Why Choose Strategically​

Cost Optimization - Claude Opus 4.5 costs approximately 67% less than Opus 4.1 ($5/$25 vs $15/$75), but still more than Sonnet 4.5. For Max users, Opus 4.5 now has roughly the same token allocation as previously had with Sonnet, making it more accessible for daily use.

Performance Balance - Sonnet 4.5 is excellent for daily coding work with superior speed and cost-efficiency. Opus 4.5 excels at state-of-the-art software engineering (SWE-bench Verified leader), complex general reasoning, and agentic workflows.

Workflow Efficiency - Using the right model for each task type optimizes both speed and quality without overspending on unnecessary capability.

Claude Sonnet 4.5 Best For:

  • Routine Coding Tasks - Excellent speed and cost-efficiency (61.4% OSWorld)
  • Daily Development - Fast iteration for most development and coding tasks
  • Feature Implementation - Standard development work and feature additions
  • Debugging & Troubleshooting - Most debugging scenarios and error resolution
  • Code Generation - Routine to moderate complexity code creation and editing
  • Documentation - Writing and editing technical documentation
  • Task Coordination - Workflow management and sub-agent orchestration
  • Cost-Sensitive Work - When speed and cost matter more than maximum capability

Claude Opus 4.5 Best For:

  • State-of-the-Art Software Engineering - SWE-bench Verified leader, complex multi-file changes
  • Agentic Workflows - Extended reasoning, computer use, browser automation
  • Enhanced Plan Mode - Clarifying questions upfront, editable plan.md files
  • Complex General Reasoning - Non-coding reasoning tasks requiring maximum capability
  • Strategic Planning - High-level planning with architectural decisions
  • Algorithm Analysis - Theoretical complexity analysis and optimization
  • Multi-Step Logic - Complex logical problems requiring deep reasoning
  • Critical Decisions - Complex reasoning where maximum capability is needed

Cost-Performance Benefits:

  • Improved Pricing - Opus 4.5 is 67% cheaper than Opus 4.1 ($5/$25 vs $15/$75)
  • Max User Efficiency - Roughly same Opus tokens as previously had with Sonnet
  • Balanced Options - Sonnet 4.5 for speed/cost, Opus 4.5 for maximum capability
  • Quality Improvement - Choose the right model for each task complexity level
  • Budget Flexibility - Lower Opus pricing and increased limits enable more usage
  • Orchestration Opportunities - Cost savings enable sub-agent delegation strategies

Use Sonnet 4.5 for routine coding work (excellent speed and cost-efficiency). Use Opus 4.5 for state-of-the-art software engineering, complex multi-file changes, and agentic workflows.

Opus 4.5 Plan Mode - Enhanced Interactive Planning​

Opus 4.5 Plan Mode brings significant improvements: uses Opus 4.5 for enhanced interactive planning with clarifying questions upfront and user-editable plan.md files before execution.

How It Works:

  1. You describe the task - Provide requirements and context
  2. Claude asks clarifying questions - About ambiguous requirements, architectural preferences, implementation choices
  3. Claude creates plan.md - Structured plan with task breakdown, dependencies, execution order
  4. You review and edit - Modify the plan as needed before execution
  5. Claude executes - Completes tasks systematically based on approved plan

Key Advantages:

  • Clarifying Questions Upfront - Resolves ambiguity before planning begins
  • Editable Plans - Review and refine execution strategy in plan.md files
  • More Thorough - 76% fewer tokens while achieving better results
  • Efficient for Max Users - Same Opus token allocation as previously had with Sonnet
  • Better Alignment - Ensure shared understanding through interactive workflow

Perfect For:

  • Complex projects with ambiguous requirements
  • Architectural decisions requiring clarification and review
  • Multi-file changes with unclear dependencies
  • Professional developers needing precise planning before execution

Activation: Select option 4 in /model command: "Use Opus 4.5 in plan mode, Sonnet 4.5 otherwise"

With Opus 4.5's enhanced Plan Mode and increased limits for Max users, this hybrid approach is now more accessible for daily complex tasks.

Recommended Strategy

Use Sonnet 4.5 as your default model for routine coding work (excellent speed and cost-efficiency). Use Opus 4.5 for state-of-the-art software engineering (SWE-bench Verified leader), agentic workflows, and complex reasoning tasks. With increased limits for Max users, Opus 4.5 is now more accessible for daily complex tasks.

Cost Awareness

Opus 4.5 is 67% cheaper than Opus 4.1 ($5/$25 vs $15/$75). For Max users, Opus 4.5 now has roughly the same token allocation as previously had with Sonnet, making it efficient for daily complex work. Choose based on task complexity: Sonnet 4.5 for routine tasks, Opus 4.5 for state-of-the-art capabilities.

Advanced practitioners balance computational expense with task complexity, creating sustainable workflows through strategic model selection and orchestrated intelligence deployment.
